The Telegraph - Calcutta : International
 Friday, September 12, 2003 				 5 million puffed to death in 2000
 London, Sept. 11 (Reuters):  Smoking killed nearly five million people in 2000, accounting  for almost equal numbers in the developed and developing  nations and painting a bleak picture for the future, scientists  said. Men accounted for three-quarters of all the deaths,  a figure rising to 84 per cent in the developing nations  where 930 million of the worlds 1.1 billion smokers are  to be found, researchers from Harvard School of Public Health  in Boston, Massachusetts and Queensland University, Australia  said in the Lancet medical journal.
